annotation: This is my most typical opening.
Quite a usual move for black.
One of the best moves in this postion that I know of.
I protected my pawn.
Threatening to take my pawn on f7 by moving his knight to g5...
...So I moved my bishop to c5.
Another move.
Uh oh I think he's got my pawn.
So I was a pwn down- at the beginning game.
Not going for the swap off.
Ok- I took the swap off now.
This is when I offered him a draw and he accepted as it was a drawish postion even though he was a pawn up.
3. Nf3 for white doesn't seem like white's best play in this situation.  It allows black to play 3...d5 which will force the bishop to eventually move.
Didn't expect to see this at all.  I was expecting either Bb5+ or a retreat to Be2.
This is poor move from me.  Thankfully my opponent didn't play 6. Qe2+ because I would've dropped that pawn I advanced.
Maybe a stronger move here would've been Bg4 pinning the knight?
Although my queen is protecting my pinned knight now she's also eying down the h2 square and hopefully I'm able to get my bishop to d6 so I can possibly snatch the pawn on h2 after Bxf3.
Had my opponent seen this he could have had a draw here.  I shouldn't have captured on a2.....Maybe Kg8 or h5 to give my king an outlet to avoid the draw.
White Resigned 0-1
As usual black fights back with a Sicilian.
The trouble with this variation is it leaves white with a rather weak center.
An unusual attack here and not a terribly useful one. It leaves the e4 pawn unsupported.
This pawn is a bit of a sticking point but it never turns into more than an annoyance.
Black is now set with the task of exchanging one of his doubled pawns for a non-doubled white pawn.
This is the threat that needs to be defended. If 16. ... c4+ 17. Be3 Qmoves 18. bxc4.
Forcing a trade of a relatively bad bishop for a good one.
? e4 is the key to this position and needs to be defended.
! If 19. Qxe5 Nxd2 and worse to follow. This capture has also given black the passed pawn that will eventually win the game.
Risky as it exposes the black king to attack along the a2-g8 diagonal but the e5 pawn needs support.
Those doubled pawns still need protection. The threatened Qe6+ is of no significant consequence whereas the black's threat of c4+ allows black to trade off one of his doubled pawns.
Black's queen makes this move possible and forces white off of the d file. Black is now trying to take advantage of white's back rank while protecting his own.
And black has managed to trade off a doubled pawn.
! Definitely the right attacking move here.
! Defends d8 a7 and c5 all at once. White has to run or trade.
Correcting black's back rank weakness but more aggressively than white's. This becomes important shortly.
To prevent an immediate Rg3 followed by attacks on g7.
Offering draw by perpetual check if white chooses to take it.
? White is better off with the draw.
! This is the most difficult step this pawn has to take towards victory.
The two alternatives Rf4 and Qf4 leave white hard-pressed to stop the e-pawn. For instance 37. Qf4 Qxf4 38. Rxf4 Rd4 39. Rf1 e3 40. Re1 Re4 and white is nearly out of options.
Otherwise e3 is met by Qe4.
Not Kh8 which would allow perpetual check. Not Rf7 which gives up too much mobility.

White has no way to stop the pawn from doing serious damage:
(A) 42. Kf2? e1=Q#
(B) 42. Rf1 exf1 0-1
(C) 42. Qxe2 Qxe2 0-1
(E) 42. Qb5 Rd1+ (E1) 43. Kf2 e1=Q# (E2) 43. Rf1 Rxf1#
(F) 42. Qf4 e1=Q+ 43. Kh2 Qxf4 44. Rxf4 e1=Q+ 45. Kh2 Qe5 0-1
Another close fought match with a few mistakes on either side which as a result could easily have gone either way
It's a long time since I have seen this opening from white so I decided to go for the centre. This is the Nimzovich-Larsen attack modern variation.
Played to avoid going a pawn down from Bxc6 b7xc6 Bxe5 which I didn't like the look of
There is only one game in the gameknot database that gets to this position
I didn't like the possibly more natural bxc6 as it totally wrecked my pawn structure this didn't look quite so bad as an alternative
This is the move that varies from the other game there Bd7 was played.
Pretty much forced as Bxg2 would be unpleasant for white
I'm still not entirely sure why I played this but it does make a claim on the centre and give me the option to castle
I won't object too much if white exchanges as I can improve my pawn structure. This move was to protect the g7 pawn from whites bishop and it was also to prepare for a future pawn storm
Here comes the pawns can I make something of it
I didn't like the look of the alternatives here
protecting the pawn and preparing an advance but white had other ideas
I had overlooked this
about the only way to get out of it without losing material that I could see.
I preferred this to cxd6 due to Re-e7 which looked pretty nasty
This seems a wasted move to me and was quite a surpise
and here it is however as I still have a pawn on c7 I can resist the pressure
If white is going to start pawn grabbing I need to try to do the same
To me Kg1 looks better as it prevents my next move
regains a pawn
From here white looks better to me particularly with his connected passed pawns
I dont understand this move
I preferred this to exchanging rooks as I was hoping to get a passer of my own
and once again completely overlooked this move. Clearly white is threatening mate
The only defence I could see from mate.
Now whites rook is a little stuck and although he can gain more material I think he has lost the initiative and I can get a passed pawn of my own
Now there is surely going to be a race for promotion I would hope that I have the advantage as my b pawn is one move ahead of whites pawns

White has to be a little careful now as I have spotted a ploy that I am hoping will get me a queen and prevent him promoting but he is short of time and his rook is in no real position to gain more time e.g. with a check
Threatens to skewer my pawn with Rb8
And now my plan comes to fruition I really liked this move probably one of the best I have played for some time.
Means that when I promote I can prevent the skewer as white will be in check
If h7 then clearly Qh6+ gains the pawn
I need to be careful that I dont allow white to push his g pawn or his king (or both) up the board too far
I'm looking to fork the pawn or rook with the king but white is too canny for that
if h7 then Qh6+
This was a shock white concedes the pawn and likely the game

Here white resigned. This was a hard fought match with mistakes on both sides in the end there was an element of luck that prevailed. I think white still had chances right up to move 49 when he seemed to throw it away.

Please comment

In this game I play a speculative sacrifice. My opponent goes wrong and loses easily. I was dissappointed that the post-game computer analysis says my sac was not the best move in the position? What do you think dear reader?  Can anyone see what an independent search engine says is best in the position?
So was start as a standard Dutch defence
Routine development.
Black decides to fianchetto her King's side Bishop too.
My knight goes to h3 so as not to block the Bg2
Still fairly standard
PLayed to ancor the Nf4 and deter g5 and also with the possibility of attacking with h5 at some stage.
The usual reply.
Taking is about White's only sensible option.
c3 scores well on the opening databases
So I attempt to follow Rukavina Dario (2194) vs. Mijatovic Vladimir (2134)
But in that game black continued with Qe7 so I have to start thinking for myself.
So I continue to develop

So does she. This is actually the first mistake according to the post game computer which gives Nfg4 11. Bd4 c5 12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. Nh3 e4 14. Nc4 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 O-O 16. h5 Be6 17. Nd6 Rab8 18. hxg6 hxg6 and a slight advantage to Black.
So I decide to make castling hard for her.
She offers the queen exchange
I avoid and hit d6.

d5 is also given as a mistake and I tend to agree. Post game computer gives Nfg4 13. Qxd6 Nxe3 14. fxe3 Bd7 15. O-O-O O-O-O 16. Bd5 Qf8 17. Qxf8 Rhxf8 18. Ne6 cxd5 19. Nxg7 Kc7 again with slight advantage to Black. But now what is Black to do about castling and developing the Bc8?
So I castle
Aha Bb7 or Ba6 is planned
So I hit c6
She defends.
Exchanging is just about forced now
She recaptures
I improve my bishop
She retreats.

Now this is the key moment. Post game computer gives 17. c4 Bb7 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Nxd5+ Bxd5 20. Bxd5 Rac8+ 21. Kb1 Rhd8 22. Nf3 Nxd5 23. Bxg7 a6 24. Nd4 Nd6 with White ahead 1.25 but I am not convinced that this is right. What do you and your search engines think?
So she takes
and I take.

And this is where she really backs out! She she gives back the piece without a fight leaving me a pawn up. The computer gives Bxf6 19. Nxd5+ Kd6 20. Nf3 Bb7 21. Nxb6+ Ke6 22. Nxa8 Rxa8 23. h5 g5 24. Rd3 g4 25. Re3+ Be4 26. Nd4+ Ke5 27. Nb5 Kd5 28. Rd1+ Kc4 as best for Black with only a slight advantage to White. I commented at the time "I am not sure that you have played the best defence you could have gone in for variations where you had 2 minor pieces v my rook and 2 maybe 3 pawns. Still material advantage to me but less clear...."
So I exchange
She recaptures
Not really aiming at the d5 pawn but aiming to put the Nf3 on d4 dominating the centre.
So now I can take the pawn d5 but why? Her bishop is tied up protecting it my pieces are so active.
so I continue to open lines
so quits the h file
I take up the dominating post
she centralises the king
I take
she takes back
I advance
She gives d5 more protection
But now I dominate the h file
She challenges it
I centralise my king
She exchanges
and again...
so I take
she takes back

she commented "Hmm Charles you could have quite easily got a second pawn but you decided to press for a mating attack down the h column - unfortunately for you it has not come off but I think I am in for a tough endgame one pawn to the bad - Joanne"

and I said "I think you are too...." a6 is given as a mistake by the post-match computer and gives … g5 30. Nd3 a5 31. Ke3 Nf7 32. Kd4 Ke6 33. a4 Bc6 34. Na7 Bb7 35. b3 Ba6 36. Nc6 Kd6 37. Nb8 Bb7 38. e3 as Black's best bet but it is still lost!
hitting the bishop
and now the pawn b6
and now her bishop is terrible! All her pawns are on the same coloured squares as her bishop blocking its movements.
Now Black cannot avoid losing a second pawn.
and now Black cannot avoid losing a third pawn so she throws in the towel. Please leave a comment or two and don't forget to rate my annotation to let me know how I am doing!
I start out with the usual king's pawn opening.
Usually I play this move.
I will develop my knight.
This is what I would have done if I were black on my first move.
I develop my other knight.
He tries to protect his two pawns.
I put up my bishop with check.
He blocks with his bishop attacking my protected bishop.
I take the trade.
H e takes it with his knight.
I put my pawn up to release my dark square bishop.
He puts his pawn out to prevent my bishop from going to g5.
I castle.
He moves another pawn up protected by the knight and blocking f4.
I bring my bishop out.
He moves his pawn down attacking my knight.
I move my knight to h4
Oops. Didn't see that coming.
I move my knight to try to get to c7.
Nope to late.
I try to free my queen.
He moves his pawn down again attacking my two pawns.
I take it with my h2 pawn which was probably a mistake.
He moves his queen up.
I trie to get my queen into the game.
He finally develops his knight attacking mine.
I move my queen and take his free pawn.
He moves his knight down to cover h2
I moved my pawn up. I should of moved my rook.
Checkmate. Please rate this annotation.
You must admit my style is weird :)
Oh look the king is ready for checkmate fastest attack available is by queen protected by the knight. We should try this beginner move.
Wrong move I guess. He should have protected his king.

Still no checkmate since the king can escape on f8 we need a bishop there.
- Bishooop are you ready?
Here I am sir!

But wait I'm under attack!
I can solve this very easy by taking the bishop with the knight.
BUT here comes my idea: if I take the bishop he might see what's coming: checkmate and ruin my plans.
So I prepared a bate for him: my rook. If I give him my rook he won't hesitate to take it and then checkmate! So I moved the king!
He took the bate :D Enjoy it!
And here I go ... I think he was surprised ;)
This is the start of the variation.  Black will reposition the N from c6 to e6 via d4. But first white's Q must be diverted.
Forced.  White doesn't want to give up the dark squares with Bxd4 and as black threatens both ...Nc2+ and ...d5 with a discovered attack the Q must move.
In the first game I annotated white played 10.Rc1. The two moves (Rc1 Qd2) are pretty much equivalent and tend to transpose to the same thing as white will probably play Rc1 later anyway.
Be3 was played in the game from part 1.
In part 1 I mentioned that I think moving this pawn is a mistake. in that game my opponent played f4 (instead of f3) and was done in by the weakened dark squares.
This strikes at the center but the real threat is ...f4! and white's bishops become very passive.
?! Missing the point of ...f4. 16.exf4 is needed here and after 16...Rxf5 17.Nd5 Qxd2 18.Rxd2 Rf7 white maintains a slight edge but black is not in any danger.
The queen exchange gains an important tempo ...
... which we use to play this move.
After ...Rf7 the rook won't have much scope. Better to defend the e-pawn with the King. Black seems to have equalized here.
further hemming in the white bishops.
Trying to activate the DSB.
?! This move I didn't understand. How will white defend this pawn now? White's play has to come on the Q-side so maybe a plan that involves pushing the Q-side pawns might be in order here?
Looking to redeploy the N to e5 via d7. Black is looking to slowly improve his position as white seems to be stuck for a plan.
?! Black now rules the dark squares with an iron fist. Instead white should look to get some Q-side play (where else will he get play?) with b4.

Either this or Rc1 as otherwise ...e6 is embarrassing for the N. 
****** EDIT ******  After further analysis it looks like white can also play in the center here with 25.e5!? the point being that 25...Bxe5 is answered with 26.Bd3! and all of a sudden the errant pawn on h6 becomes a huge asset for white! Also 25.e5!? e6 26.Nc3 Bxe5 27.Nb4 and white has some activity for the pawn though I don't know if it's enough compensation.
The bishop goes to pick up white's wayward h-pawn.
Black is winning.
! Played only after double-counting the pawn moves ;)  Black's King can infiltrate on the dark squares!

! This is now an easy win for black. The plan is Be8->Bc6 ...h5 and ...g4 creating a passed pawn. White's K can't both defend against this and keep the black K from infiltrating on d4 so white is lost.
Black's plan was to move the B to c6 and then play ...h5 and ...g4 creating a passed pawn. But with the white B off the d1-h5 diagonal we can speed things up.
Now white is in Zugzwang.  Every move loses: K move (or BxB) allows the black king to infiltrate on d4 or e4 B move loses g2 pawn and moving either g-pawn loses material.
White's K can't defend everything.
Seemed to be the quickest way. ...Kxc4 works too.
White can resign here.  The rest of the game is not interesting my opponent decided to play it out until he was checkmated.
I started the Scandinavian Defense here.  I wanted to give it a go a good test to see if I can get a good game out of it.
My queen is being attacked here.  Although it doesn't follow the line exactly she's being shrewd not to chase my queen all over the board.
Here I castled.  It's becoming an interesting game.

A queen fork is scary.  However this woman has a suitable strategy.  She waits until she can get into a position where she could cause a trade.  Notice though that I haven't taken the pawn.  studentofkerry had claimed the file already with her rook. I have challenged her claim and now I'm waiting for the perfect moment to claim the e file for myself.  It has become a waiting game where one of us could make a mistake.

Here is where studentofkerry made her mistake.  She could have moved her Queen Rook to c1 but she moved her King Rook to c1. it would have been interesting then.  She'd have the e file and would have won the game.
Here is where I grabbed the second rank -- the seventh rank to me playing as black.  Studentofkerry is now doomed to lose.
Here we moved to Checkmate.  I feel sorry of course but she will continue to play chess and win more games.  I guess you have to lose many games of chess before you attain Grandmaster status.
All the games started here with White to play.
Ducking forward. In general I'm trying to be less passive in my games.
Continuing to develop.
Completing the exchange.
Now I have to retreat to interpose against the check.
Here I have to retreat. There are no available squares to advance to.
I opt for the exchange.
Finally I tuck my King safely away [and incidentally unpin my Knight.]
Preparing to challenge White's powerful central Pawns.
Attacking the advanced QP. White goes in for the exchange.
Now his B must move. I was expecting 18 B-R6 forcing my Rook to move but he chooses a straight retreat.
Moving the Knight to a further-advanced position.
I'm hoping White thinks I'm only moving here to block the Bishop's diagonal...
...and overlooks my real intentions. He did and I reveal them now with a rooyal fork.
With decisive material gain.
White has a little bit of fight left in him...
....but now he calls a halt graciously resigning.

I'm not familiar with this opening so I just play a classical style.  I can't see any reason for black to prefer one center pawn over the other.  d5 seems to be marginally the more popular response as it turns out.
This is probably the most sensible way to develop that bishop at this point and it's one of the moves that really established the character of the game...
...because it allows this pawn advance to lock up the center pretty rigidly.  White's going to have to look for opportunities to make his finachettoed light-square bishop effective.
Black's pretty happy with the exchange as it leaves his queen in a nice place with no minor pieces likely to threaten it in the short term.

At this point things felt fairly equal to me (playing as black) but it seemed like the one advantage that was up for grabs was queenside space.  A lot of lines I tried ended with white dominating that space so...
...this check looks kind of pointless since it can be blocked (and indeed counterproductive since white's pawns are going to advance while I retreat my bishop)...

...but the point was to exchange the knight for a better claim on the space.  At this point you can read the shape of the rest of the game:  white's going to be trying to loosen up his pieces and form them into an attack force and black will just (1) ward off any threats as they come and (2) advance a pawn whenever possible.  The feasibility of (1) is the key question of course.  I reckoned that white's inactive bishop on g2 meant that the actual active material was still pretty even. 

I simply haven't got enough experience to decide if this was a really sound plan or not; perhaps readers will weigh in.  The computer strongly dislikes it but the hoped-for advantage is a rather far-off one.
I was expecting 11. Nbd2.  I'm not sure what the motivation for Kf1 was but white's king's rook probably would have argued against it.

This was a flat-out mistake.  White could now take the e-pawn safely 12. Nxe5 and free his own e-pawn to advance.  If white recaptures with 12...Qxe5 then 13.Qa4+ regains the material with increased mobility for white too.  Black could have ruled out the pesky check by simply  11...O-O.
Black's just clearing out the back rank so that the rooks can move freely and back up pawns as needed.
White's steadily building up pressure on the kingside...
...and swinging another piece that direction.
If 16..c5 which was my initial thought then white has the option to bring his knight to c4 which seemed troublesome.  b5 at least limits that.
The Plan: push a pawn whenever possible.

There was just too much attacking force building up near my king so this exchange damps it down again.  In general since I'm trying to win with pawns I don't have many objections to exchanging off pieces.
The computer doesn't seem to indicate any strong advantage to capturing with the e-pawn or the g-pawn but I would have been strongly inclined as white to get that e-pawn off of my bishop's diagonal.

I'm not sure if that pawn was an oversight or if it was a calculated loss.  I had to think quite a bit about whether I should grab it or whether that would just cost me time.  It seems like 22. Qb1 would have put a watcher on the b-pawn without abandoning white's own a-pawn.

This looked like a strangely backward move at first glance but it makes sense: the black queen is trying to do several jobs at the moment and maneuvering the knight to g4 where it can harass her is natural.
In fact I didn't want to hassle with staving that off so another damping exchange is offered...
...and accepted.
This is convenient since I needed to get that bishop out of the way to let the a-pawn advance anyway.
White's KR says "YES!"
The Plan.

Losing the c-pawn and even the bishop was going to be acceptable if I could drive home Little Pawn A and/or Little Pawn B.  At this point as far as I can tell white can only stop that at the cost of a rook.
...maneuvering to get the bishop aimed at the queening square.
Clearing the way for the bishop; also threatening the pawn on d3 (which would clear a path forward for the black d-pawn).
The cost of all that is that black's king has just about buggerall left in the way of defense and white still has dangerous pieces about.

Threatening Rh8# if black isn't alert!  Given the situation it makes sense to allow black every possibility to hang himself through carelessness.   This reminds me of 32... Ne4 in Reshevsky vs Najdorf (http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1101450) a game I enjoyed playing through recently.
The computer says this is mate in 7.  I didn't realize that at the time but I knew it was mate if white took the rook - the mating sequence beginning with QxP is all forced moves.
...and indeed.

That was an excellent hard-fought battle with a lot more tension than the breezy comments made in comfortable hindsight would indicate.  Games where white and black have differing plans and are racing to advance their own while thwarting the other are always fascinating.

Hi everyone!

This game got off to another slow start for me but later on in the game white overlooked a knight fork winning the exchange.  This was not a family fork that came later and finished off my opponent at the end.  The first mistake however put this skids right on.  So how did this happen?  Well read on.  Here is the computer analysis: http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=16201874&fb=1&rnd=0.03848212663100348.  The first four moves are the main line Ruy Lopez.
5. Qe2 - unusual.
5. ...... b5 - might as well drive white back.
8. ..... d3 - time for some quiet line-opening development.
11. cxd4 - pawn trade.

12. ..... Ne4 - I decided to make use of a temporary outpost for my knight as it will take a few moves for white to give a possible f3.  I did think for one horrible moment that BxP would remove the rampant knight's protector and it would be zapped by the Wicked Witch of the West but never fear d5 is also defended by Glenda!
14. ..... f5 - bolsters my knight.
16. ..... b4 - exerts a cramp on c3 and a3 and the only way the white QKt can get to is d2.  He does move his knight to d2 but allows ......
12. Nbd2?? ...... wait for it ......

17. ..... Nc3 - ..... a knight fork!  Now one move previously it looked as though that fork was not possible as the b1 knight was defending c3.  As it is no longer defending that square I take full advantage of this fact.
19. Bxd1 - so now I am the exchange up Eureka!
19. ..... f4 - another Eureka moment white's dsb is trapped and my pawn takes advantage of that and now I am rook for pawn up double Eureka!
21. .... Bg6 - and white is gonna lose yet more wood!
22. Qe3 - the Witch attacks my rook but here comes a desperado.
23. ..... Bxc2 (LPDO) - loose pieces drop off.
25. e6 - white ain't gonna wave that white flag yet.  He tries to counter-attack with a central passer.  I must remain alert.
25. ...... Qd6 - Glenda moves off her home square and immediately puts pressure on that passer.
26. ..... Re8 - it is always a good idea to put your rook in line with the enemy queen.  Leaves open a lot of pinning possibilities.  If you have your queen in line with an enemy rook - beware!
27. ..... Nc6 - eyeing up d8 for pile-on purposes.  That knight is destined for far better things however.
28. ..... Bf6 - not much to do except put pressure on d4 and open up another attacker on e6.

29. ...... Be4 - that e6 pawn has been cut off from its defenders and it is not long for this world - so it seems - but incredibly that pawn survives the rest of the game albeit looking extremely forlorn!
30. Ng5?? - only because of this move!
30. .... Bxg5 - I have something up my sleeve ...... wait for it ......
31. Qxg5 ..... wait for it ......

31. ....... Nxd4.  Now!!!  White does wave the white flag because a family fork is threatened.  Do you see where?  Either the Wicked Witch or white's remaining rook must drop should white move his king to f1.  White is already 6 points down in material and is about to lose a shedload more.  I would think even the Master Mater had this position against me (I wish!) he would not want to continue here.  Anyhow I may have another game for you on the theme of knight forks coming up but that one is still in play so it is another case of watch this space.  Anyhow - hope you all have a nice evening - bye for now - Joanne
e4. A standard choice for me which I tend to do better with thn d4.
Black opts for the Sicilian. A solid choice against e4 which statistically has the best results for wins and draws.
Standard developing move which controls d4 and d5.
Protecting the pawn and e5.
Clearly the Najdorf Sicilian which works well for black by creating opportunities on the Queen side.
Eying off the vulnerable e7 square.
Attacking the bishop while developing the Queen to a useful square.
Retreating the bishop while maintaining pressure on the e7 square.
This Queen side pawn push starts an early attack for white while freeing up the b7 square for the light square bishop.

Developing the dark square bishop and protecting the knight on d4. If black continues to push his b pawn then I anticipated Nd5. The alternative move I considered was f3 keeping blacks Knight off of g4.
As anticipated...
Nd4 attacking the Queen and anticipating and exchange of Knights.

Rather than exchange bishops on the d7 square I wanted to maintain development and move toward castling but at this stage not sure which side. I was a bit concerned about the Queenside pawns so will probably castle king side.
Protecting the pawn on f7 with blacks Queen while attacking the knight on d4.
Trading off bishops.
I made this move some time after my previous move and forgot about the knight being attacked on d4. A mistake I often make in correspondence chess. Fingers crossed he misses it.
Phew. Developing the knight and attacking my knight I decide to trade off.

Trading knights. At this point in the game the material is even. Advantages for white are that I have castled and development is proceeding. However I have a couple of unprotected pawns. Black has not yet castled but has advances and opportunities on the Queenside.
Protecting the pawn attacked by the black Queen and occupying a semi-open file.
Hmmm. Dilemma. Black attacks my a pawn and I as much as I looked I could not see any way to stop going a pawn down.
I decided to give him the c pawn to open the file up. May come in useful later on to mount an attack on the uncastled king.
Protecting the pawn
Retreating the queen and protecting the Rook.
Devloping the Rook onto the open file while attacking the Queen.
I played this move to give black some castling problems. If he moves his bishop to e7 I can ttake his g7 pawn leavins his king in the open.
Preparing to fianchetto the bishop and castle to safety.

Time to free up some lines and get my Rook into the action. If he captures the pawn I will take with the bishop giving me a nice Queen and bishop battery. I didn't think he would because he is in despearate need of castling.
Preparing to castle.
Pushing the pawn to further my attack.
? Perhaps was unsure about castling.
f6!This move really cramps blacks position and makes the black king vulnerable at the same time limits blacksbishop and h Rook.
Retreating to safety.
Time to put some pressure on and attack down open and semi-open files.
Attacking the f-pawn and unpinning the Queen.
Protecting the important f-pawn
Looking to make some space and attacking down the king side bringing the Rook into play. Also gives the bishop an attacking square to get to on h6.
Putting pressure on the d6 pawn. Now if black plays Bh6 the d6 pawn will fall putting pressure on the Queen to find a safe square to get to.
Attacking the Rook and protecting d6 but brings the king on to a vulnerable square.
Boubling the Rooks and preparing to give chack on c7. At this point black is in a pretty tight spot. His development is poor Rooks are not connected and he has some serious threats on the king.
In an attempt to connect Rooks and trade off my attackers.
Rc7! This move I believe seals the game and gives black no real options.
Retreating the King.

Hi everyone!

..... in this game I managed to stay alert and patient and I tried something on the kingside late on in the endgame and it worked!  Yup I have conceded a couple of low draws lately in my rated games because there seemed to be no way whatsoever of forcing a victory (and one of those low draws was against Delta the Master Blaster who I knew not to mess with!).  Class B and C players are certainly capable of nasty things against me so I know when to hold out the olive branch.  However in this case I got lucky.  Here is how it goes (it starts off with a Scandinavian/Centre Counter Defense with 1. e4 d5) and here is the gameknot analysis.http://gameknot.com/analyze-board.pl?bd=16301005&rnd=0.1441176371074478
2. ...... Qxd5 - the main line.  It does bring out the queen very early but this defense can pack a punch.
3. ..... Qa5 - this is considered the best square in the Centre Counter.  It will take a few moves before I can harass the Wicked Witch of the West.
5. Nf3 - development.
7. Bd2 - Fou Lenoir emerges and lines up against the Witch.
8. Qe2 - and Glenda puts pressure on e6.
11. Bxc3 - B for N trade.
14. ..... Nd5 - over the last few moves there have been a series of trades and we are now moving towards an endgame.
15. ...... 0-0 and black castles kingside.
17. ..... B for N trade and we now have opposite bishops.  Both pairs of rooks are on so there is still some possibility of a result here.
20. ..... Rac8 - a doubling on the c column but one of the rooks is about to be traded off.
22. Bxc3 - voila!
24. ..... Bh7 - not much happening here.  Can I make things happen?
24. Rd4 - I try.
27. Rh4 - my finger has been hovering over the Offer Draw button for the last few moves.  I now see that I can certainly make something happen here though.  First I make the h6 pawn a target.
28. g4 - and now the h pawn is pinned against the black lsb I pile up on it.
29. b3 - black's move looked aggressive but I think I can foil his plans.  Whatever I do though I must not put Henry on d3 - can you see why not?
30. Ke3 - so now Henry goes to e3 and suddenly his rook is ........ trapped.
32. Rxg5 - and now black must lose heavy material.
33. Rxg6 - black can now avoid losing his rook by fxe5 but he will be a piece and a pawn down.  My opponent decided this was too much and waved the white flag.  A nice ending.
Played at the Emerald City Open in Seattle 2011.  Igor was not only rated 340 points higher than me he's also over 20 years younger.  So I had my work cut out for me in this game.
The Grand Prix Attack.  Aggressive but not completely solid.  Fortunately I was well prepared against this opening having a friend who plays it consistently.
The idea is to play d5 quickly forcing white to either allow the exchange of the e-pawn or push e5 which immobilizes the center.
It's necessary to keep white from playing Bb5 as the pin on the knight interferes with the d5 push.
White opts to exchange.  This breaks up his attacking formation and leaves the f-pawn looking somewhat off-sides.
Blocking against checks on the e-file after Re1.
This looks inaccurate to me (even though Fritz doesn't find anything wrong with it) since it allows Ne4 doubling white's pawns.
Since both Nxe4 and Bd2 drop a pawn this seems to be best.
Here I decide that my plan will be to drum up counter-play on the c-file.
The bishop needs to retreat here rather than to b6 in order to help defend against white's forthcoming kingside attack.
Heading to f5 and opening the c-file for my rooks.
black will meet 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Bxd5 with 18. ... Bxd5 19. Qxd5 Ne3 with a nice fork.
Finally I have time to start bringing my rooks to the c-file.
white misses his opportunity to gain an advantage with 25. g6!
a nice finesse

Now my plan bears fruit.  With my heavy pieces in position on the c-file I have sufficient counter-play to neutralize his attack on the e-file.  My task is made easier by the weakness of white's kingside on the diagonals - a weakened king position is the price white paid for his early aggression.
Forced.
Freeing the rook.
It doesn't seem to make much difference what to capture with most of the heavy pieces are coming off either way.
Protecting e7 which will allow me to defend the 7th rank.

Fritz evaluates this position as a dead draw.  During the game I considered playing Rd8 and hoping the advanced g & f pawns would turn out to be vulnerable but wisdom got the better of me and I opted to avoid any further complications against my higher-rated opponent.
Drawn - which was a moral victory for me as all my other recent outings against experts have gone into the loss column.
I was hoping for a Fried liver.
This is the Giucco Piano. I could've played many moves such as b4 or the main line which is c3.
Instead I choose a safer route.
If d6 i would play b4. Captain Evans who invented the Evans Gambit won against McConnell when 4. Bc4 d6 5.b4 and he got crushed.
He's starting to copy me.
Making an escape square for thr bishop
Drops a pawn
g4 had to be the biggest blunder. The knight has infiltrated and I have made many weaknesses.
If 24. Rf3 attacking the knight  24. ....  Ne2+ forks the king and queens. IT shouldn't be too hard to defeat me after.
I didn't take the knight. Why not? I don't even know myself.
drops another pawn to launch a discovered attack on my rook.
He obviously didn't calculate properly.

There was a mate on g8 which he obviously didn't see. This was supposed to be his win as his pieces are more active and all my pieces are on the queenside and I can't really defend my queen. I was lucky to win this.
The opening is standard fare.
To avoid a severe weaking of my Pawns if White had played BxKN. If he plays BxQN now my Q will recapture and my Pawn structure in front of my castled K wil remain intact.
To unpin my KBP in preparation for driving Black's QB.
Clearing the square for my Rook.
Gaining a small material advantage. Now my job is to swap off some of the pieces. The more wood leaves the board the bigger the advantage of one Pawn looms.
Forcing the horseman to retreat.
I was expecting the White Q to zip back along the diagonal behind its lines. But...
To my surprise White allows the exchange of Q's. One very major piece for each side leaves the board simplifying the position.
Looking to swap down more...
...and White does my job for me. The "small" material advantage is getting bigger by the move.
If White doesn't want to lose another Pawn more wood must now come off.
A pair of minors vanishes.
I lock the Q-side where I have a protected passed Pawn.
With four pieces left for each side there's still the possibility of complications. I add extra defenses to the King's wing.
Looking to swap down further...
...and I do winning a minor exchange to boot.
Now I have to guard my base Pawn on the Q-side.
I retreat and reconnect my Rooks.
Activating the B.
Securing the K where the white Rooks can't reach it.
Even in endgames you see the struggle for a tempo at times. I simply mark time here.
Looking to swap down further.
Hoping for 37 PxB which would also let me swap a pair of Rooks...
...but this time White doesn't play into my hands. The ending with 2 Rooks and Pawns on both sides is called by the great Capablanca the most difficult of all endings.
Freeing my Rook.
Naturally I wish to push my passed Pawn.
I see a chance to simplify down while maintaining my material advantage. The passed Pawn is bait...
...and White swallows it.
After White's 42nd move I can get rid of BOTH remaining pairs of Rooks. I was only trying to swap off one pair...
...but I gratefully take the opportunity to dump both pairs.
Now all the pieces are gone and my extra Pawn is an enormous advantage. White's K has to defend both flanks.
I feint towards the Q-side where I have a material edge...
...and now quickly switch to the K-side where I threaten to massacre White's pawns.
White hopes to neutralize my K-side Pawns as well...
...but now I'm one vital tempo ahead.
If White plays 50 KxP 50... KxP and my K will escort the KNP to the promotion square.
White now must move his K away from his KNP...
...which I promptly capture. When trying to promote a Pawn during a K and P end game it is always best to have your K *in front* of the P -- exactly where I have mine.
Clearing the path.
White resigns.  The finish would be 54 K-R4 K-B6 55 K-R5 P-N6 and the Pawn cannot be stopped from Queening.

The pawn push is the most common way of meeting the Ruy Lopez. It is known as the Morphy defense and the idea is pretty simple. Since white can't capture the e4 pawn immediately blaack will try to kick off the bishop and play b5 if needed.

Ba4 is the retreat variation. It is the most popular variation. The other variation is the exchange variation which is aimed to damage the pawn structure of black but white ends up exchanging his most powerful minor piece for it.

Anaylsis of the position:

1. center control: Both players have equal control of the center. However while the isolated e-pawn can be a future strong asset for white it is at present weaker than black's center pawn. no one has the advantage.
2. Piece development and position: Both players have the same amount of pieces developed and are well centralized. No one has the advantage
3. King Safety: Black is clearly better here because black is ready to castle while white still is two or three moves from castling to safety. Advantage for Black
4. Tactical threats and open lines: White has strong pressure on d5 but at present has no real way to exploit it. While black has more tangible pressure on e5 because Black can use of the f-file to gain tempo against the undefended bishop. Also at black's disposal is the possiblity of d5-d4 thrust creating a uncomfortable pinch on c3. In conclusion based on the fact tha black has more tangible tactical threats better use of the open lines and stronger initative black is clearly better.

So based upon the for mentioned analysis I have deviced the following play. 1. Increase the safety of my king and gain tempo on the undefended bishop. 2. liquidate my only weakness(the d-pawn) by forcing the exchange on c3. 3. complete my development 4. fight for control of the centre by centralizing my remaining peices.

Black chooses to castle here - given this choose of move I think Black might have been better castling last move.
As it stands at this position White has a very strong advantage - both materially and spatially.
White is relentless in attacking the Black King by making use of the pin of the g7 pawn and threatening checkmate.

Black tries to trap the White Bishop with a pawn push but further weakens his castle. 8. Ng6 would have prevented the mating threat and forced the bishop to move away... However Black would have won his piece back with Nf5 using the Rook on e8 to pin the pawn to e4.
White attacks the weak pawn structure in front of the Black King which will also release his rook.

Black finally develops a queen-side piece but I wonder if Ng6 might have been more suitable in this situation... as well as providing some support to the king it gives Black some counterplay with the threat on e4.
Black's defense is starting to crumble from under him.
Black chooses to attack and takes back a pawn on d4 threatening the fork at c2.
White develops another piece to the attack with a check.

This is the best move for Black giving up a pawn but opening up the Bishop's c8-f1 diagonal. 11... Kh8 12. gxf6 would lose for Black. 12... Ng6 13. Bg7# or 12... Rg8 13. Qg7+ Rxg7 14. Bxg7# or 12... Nf5 (either knight) 13. Qg7+ Nxg7 14. Bxg7#.
Discovered check attacking the knight and threatening checkmate. 12... Kh8 clearly loses.
Only move for Black to continue with.
White continues on relentlessly taking the d5 pawn to check the Black King.
11... d5 earlier means that this is playable too developing another piece for Black. Kh8 is clearly mate again from Bg7.

White chooses to grab another piece putting him +11 up in material terms at this moment. White's King is in the middle of the board with little support and I think White underestimates how quickly Black can now mobilise for an attack on that King. Black has a forced mate in four here.
I like this move a lot - many players will re-take a piece just because they assume they must. Black ignores the Bishop to mount an attack of his own.
Only move as 15. Kf1 Qd1#.
Black continues the attack forcing the king towards the centre. His only flight square now is f3.
Black misses a forced mate in two here with 16... Qd1+ 17. Ne2 Qxe2# but continues his attack with Qf6+ trying to close his pieces in around the White King.
White blocks the check from the Queen with his bishop.
Black releases the pin on the knight by moving the King - he chooses to ignore both the Bishop and Rook threatening mate in one.
White tries to develop attacking the LSB... he misses Black's checkmate.

And in one swift Knight move rekraparker gets an unexpected win even though he is down by a Rook Bishop and pawn. I want to congratulate rekraparker on effort in this game trying relentlessly even when it looked like White had got well on top of him.

Thank you all for reading.
